.TH "RANGE.CREATECONTEXTUALFRAGMENT" "3JS" "December 29, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Range.createContextualFragment \- Range: createContextualFragment()
method
.SH SYNOPSIS
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] This method parses its input as HTML or XML, writing
the result into a \f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R] that might subsequently be
injected into the DOM.
APIs like this are known as injection sinks, and are potentially a
vector for cross\-site scripting (XSS) attacks, if the input originally
came from an attacker.
.PP
You can reduce the risk by assigning \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] objects
instead of strings, and enforcing trusted types using the
\f[CR]require\-trusted\-types\-for\f[R] CSP directive.
This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function,
which has the chance to sanitize the input to remove potentially
dangerous markup, such as \f[CR]<script>\f[R] elements and event handler
attributes.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]Range.createContextualFragment()\f[B]\f[R] method of the
\f[CR]Range\f[R] interface returns a \f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R]
representing the parsed input HTML or XML.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
createContextualFragment(input)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]input\f[R]
A \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] instance or string that represents the text and
tags to be converted to a document fragment.
.SS Return value
A \f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R] object.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if the property is set to a string when Trusted Types are
enforced by a CSP and no default policy is defined.
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[B]\f[CB]Range.createContextualFragment()\f[B]\f[R] method returns
a \f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R] by invoking the HTML fragment parsing
algorithm or the XML fragment parsing algorithm with the start of the
range (the \f[I]parent\f[R] of the selected node) as the context node.
.PP
The HTML fragment parsing algorithm is used if the range belongs to a
\f[CR]Document\f[R] whose HTMLness bit is set.
In the HTML case, if the context node would be \f[CR]html\f[R], for
historical reasons the fragment parsing algorithm is invoked with
\f[CR]body\f[R] as the context instead.
.SS Security considerations
The method does not perform any sanitization of the input to remove
XSS\-unsafe elements such as \f[CR]<script>\f[R], or event handler
content attributes.
If the input is provided by a user, and the returned
\f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R] is subsequently injected into the DOM, this
method can be therefore become a vector for cross\-site scripting (XSS)
attacks.
.PP
For example, the following code would inject the potentially dangerous
user\-provided string into the DOM.
.PP
\f[B]Bad\f[R]
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] untrustedCode = \(dq<script>alert(\(aqPotentially evil code!\(aq);</script>\(dq;

\f[B]const\f[R] range = document.createRange();
\f[I]// Make the parent of the first div in the document become the context node\f[R]
range.selectNode(document.getElementsByTagName(\(dqdiv\(dq).item(0));
\f[B]const\f[R] documentFragment = range.createContextualFragment(untrustedCode);
document.body.appendChild(documentFragment);
.EE
.PP
When inserting HTML into a page using
\f[CR]createContextualFragment()\f[R], you should pass
\f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] objects instead of strings, and enforce trusted
types using the \f[CR]require\-trusted\-types\-for\f[R] CSP directive.
This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function,
which has the chance to sanitize the input to remove potentially
dangerous markup before it is injected.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using \f[CR]createContextualFragment()\f[R] with \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R]
Trusted types are not yet supported on all browsers, so first we define
the trusted types tinyfill.
This acts as a transparent replacement for the Trusted Types JavaScript
API:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (\f[B]typeof\f[R] trustedTypes === \(dqundefined\(dq)
  trustedTypes = { createPolicy: (n, rules) \f[B]=>\f[R] rules };
.EE
.PP
Next we define a policy named \f[CR]some\-content\-policy\f[R] to create
\f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] objects from the input (we should also enforce
the \f[CR]some\-content\-policy\f[R] using CSP).
The code implements a no\-op policy in order to allow this example to
work without a third\-party dependency.
Your own application code should use a third\-party library such as the
\(lqDOMPurify\(rq library to return sanitized content from the untrusted
input.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] policy = trustedTypes.createPolicy(\(dqsome\-content\-policy\(dq, {
  createHTML(input) {
    \f[B]return\f[R] input; \f[I]// Do not do this in your own code!\f[R]
    \f[I]// Instead do something like:\f[R]
    \f[I]// return DOMPurify.sanitize(input);\f[R]
  },
});

\f[B]const\f[R] unsafeText = \(dq<script>alert(\(aqPotentially evil code!\(aq);</script>\(dq;
\f[B]const\f[R] trustedHTML = policy.createHTML(unsafeText);
.EE
.PP
We can then create a \f[CR]DocumentFragment\f[R] using our trusted
version of the original text, and safely append it to the document:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] range = document.createRange();

\f[I]// Make the parent of the first div in the document become the context node\f[R]
range.selectNode(document.getElementsByTagName(\(dqdiv\(dq).item(0));
\f[B]const\f[R] documentFragment = range.createContextualFragment(trustedHTML);
document.body.appendChild(documentFragment);
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
The DOM interfaces index
